</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Advancing Medical Innovation: The Current System -- PFF</TITLE></HEAD><BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small>
<h3>APPENDIX:  DRUG DEVELOPMENT AND REGULATION
-- THE CURRENT SYSTEM</FONT></h3>
</FONT>
<P>
<B>How a Drug is Developed</B>
<P>
FDA does not test drugs itself.  The development
of a new drug is undertaken by a sponsor, which -- because of
the time, complexity, and costs of the process -- is almost always
a pharmaceutical company.  (Occasionally -- in about 5 percent
of approved drugs -- a federal agency, university, hospital, or
research institution may discover compounds, obtain patents, and
start development, but such entities almost never have the resources
and specialized skills to take a drug through the full development
process to obtain NDA approval themselves.) <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
Development of a new drug generally begins
with the testing of a great many chemical compounds in in-vitro
screens. (In the case of biologics, fewer substances are screened).
 Then they are screened in laboratory animals in order to determine
possible toxicity and therapeutic activity. These preclinical
investigations define the pharmacological and toxicological properties
of the agent and help to predict the initial dose range for humans.
 Many of the agents screened are eliminated from further development
at this stage, usually because they are ineffective, toxic, or
not absorbed.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
When animal studies suggest that a compound
may be therapeutically promising, the sponsor moves on to Phase
I clinical testing, which introduces the drug into humans for
the first time.  The sponsor must submit to FDA an application
called an IND (Investigational New Drug filing).  FDA has 30 days
to review the submission to ensure that the product is reasonably
safe for research in human subjects.  If FDA does not formally
object, the sponsor may begin clinical testing after the 30 days.
 Uncertainty at this stage about whether FDA will object, request
more data, or require different test procedures is highly disruptive
and has often caused U.S. companies to use more predictable locations
abroad for initial human testing.   (Currently, a significant
fraction of U.S. companies' Phase I testing is performed abroad,
mainly in Great Britain and elsewhere in Europe.  This has occurred
to such an extent that the Phase I testing industry in the United
States has collapsed; many facilities are now closed.) <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
Clinical studies are loosely divided into three
phases that represent a logical progression, or scale-up, of study
size and complexity.  Phases I and IIA, together considered to
be early clinical research, involve, respectively, the first administration
of a drug to normal human subjects and the first test of efficacy
in patients.  Phase I may involve as few as 20 subjects, and Phase
II a few dozen to a few hundred.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
Usually after early Phase II (Phase IIA), a
decision is made as to whether the drug offers sufficient promise
to warrant larger-scale (Phase IIB-III) clinical trials in order
to develop the product for marketing.  Only about a third of the
drugs that start in human testing survive to enter Phase III.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
In Phase III, research expands to examine the
following:  (i) the drug's effectiveness and side-effects in a
larger number and varied types of patients and, often, a wider
range of disease conditions (&quot;indications&quot;); (ii) the
types and incidence of side-effects; (iii) the potential for long-term
use and interactions with other drugs; and (iv) other information
useful for drug labeling. Phase III trials may involve from several
hundred to several thousand patients.  <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
Although Phase III trials cost more money and
take more time than any other single component of the development
process, the earlier phases -- and the effect of ponderous regulation
of them -- are perhaps even more important in determining the
time and cost of drug development.  There are high attrition rates
(failures) of drug candidates at the early stages when little
is known about them, and there are far more products under investigation
at the early stages. These facts are often overlooked, but they
underscore the key importance of obtaining greater efficiency
and cost reductions in the earlier phases of the drug development
process.  Such improvements would facilitate early decisions to
drop compounds that will ultimately fail (that is to say, the
majority), in order to focus resources on the few that will succeed.</FONT>
<P>
 </FONT>
<P>
Although the process is described in terms
of phases, development is really a continuum of research.  In
practice, the phases of drug testing are not sharply differentiated.
 Often, studies described as Phase I may have to be done or repeated
after Phase II -- or even Phase III -- has begun. For instance,
after advanced clinical testing in adults, the sponsor might seek
a pediatric indication; new Phase I and II studies might then
be needed in children.  Often, many different types of studies
are done simultaneously for different purposes; they are not neatly
divided into phases.  <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
The distinction between &quot;early&quot; and
&quot;later&quot; clinical research, is the junction between Phase
IIA and Phase IIB.  Through Phase IIA (sometimes called &quot;exploratory
development&quot;) researchers are looking for evidence of &quot;clinical
proof of concept,&quot; and expenditures through this point are
generally less than about $15 million per compound, most of which
fail.  After Phase IIA, drug testing enters an intense program
focused primarily on amassing evidence of efficacy for ultimate
NDA approval.  Expenditures for Phase III programs are in the
tens of millions to  hundreds of millions of dollars.  (One cardiovascular
drug reached the quarter-billion dollar mark in a multicenter
Phase III clinical trial -- and failed).<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B>The NDA Submission and Review Process</B>
<P>
When the pre-clinical and clinical testing
demonstrate that a drug is effective as labeled and reasonably
safe, the sponsor files a New Drug Application (or Product Licensing
Application -- PLA -- in the case of biologics) with FDA, seeking
approval to market the drug.  The NDA, which consists of many
volumes and often hundreds of thousands of pages, describes fully
the reports of all investigations and statistical analyses performed
to demonstrate the drug's safety and effectiveness.  It also includes
a description of the drug's composition, the methods, facilities,
and controls for the manufacturing, processing, and packaging
of the drug; samples of the drug and its components; and a draft
version of the proposed labeling.  NDAs are reviewed by the Office
of Drug Evaluation in FDA's Center for Drug Evaluation and Research
(CDER), and PLAs are reviewed by the Center for Biologics Evaluation
and Research (CBER).  The reviews are performed by teams consisting
of physicians, pharmacologists, chemists, statisticians, and other
specialists.  By statute, FDA is required to approve or disapprove
an NDA within 180 days, although this rarely happens.  The 180-day
period can be extended by &quot;agreement&quot; between the sponsor
and FDA.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
Ultimately, most NDA submissions (at present
85 percent; DiMasi et al., CPT 1994, 1995) are approved by FDA,
but frequently final approval comes only after considerable time
and negotiation and requires additional submissions of data. 
Also FDA may narrow the sponsor's initial request, approving fewer
indications for the drug's use and imposing more restrictive labeling
requirements. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
After passage of the 1962 Amendments, the time
required for FDA review and approval of NDAs rose from six months
in 1962 to an average of three years in 1975 and remained there
throughout the 1970s and 1980s (ranging as high as four-year averages
at times); after years of protest by the industry and efforts
by FDA and industry, the time required has now been reduced to
two years or less.  The sharpest reduction occurred recently with
the implementation of user fees (but before most of the additional
personnel approved by PDUFA -- the User Fee Act -- had been hired
by FDA, suggesting that most of the effect was due to a management
change that could have been implemented at any time during the
preceding 25 years).  Much has been made of FDA's efforts to reduce
the time of NDA review, but even substantial reductions, while
desirable, will not greatly affect the overall 15-year total time
required for drug development and review.  Provided gross excesses
in review times do not reappear, the proper focus now should be
to reduce the time and costs of the total development and approval
cycle, and this will need more strategic attention to the endpoints
required for approval, as well as to the tactical efforts needed
to achieve them.  <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
Meanwhile the number of new INDs has continued
to rise, but the trickle of products approved for market that
emerge from the end of the pipeline has remained stagnant at 20
to 30 per year since the 1960s.  In 1994 the FDA approved only
22 new drugs (compared to 25 the previous year).   The numbers
of applications submitted to FDA for marketing approval of biologicals
has been declining.  Thus, the flow of products from the first
clinical trials through to ultimate marketing approval has slowed.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
These are some of the reasons that this proposal
seeks to make improvements throughout the period of regulated
clinical testing, rather than focusing predominantly on expediting
NDA review and approval.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P><br></blockquote><center><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small><P><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT16-B21-37</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA024-000258-B011-258</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.sbsc.org:80/pff/mip/3.html 204.71.237.86 19970108153827 text/html 6181
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Wednesday, 08-Jan-97 15:38:44 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 11-Jul-96 19:36:10 GMT
Content-length: 5993
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Advancing Medical Innovation: New Device Certification Process -- PFF</TITLE></HEAD><BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small>

<h2>III. Medical Devices</h2>
by Ralph A. Epstein<P>

<CENTER><B>EXECUTIVE SUMMARY<BR>
</B></CENTER>
<P>
<b>Operating Plan for a New Medical Device
Certification Process</b>
<P>
The new plan involves the interaction of three
groups: the manufacturer who bears the ultimate responsibility
for their product; a private Device Certifying Body (DCB), engaged
by the manufacturer to provide independent certification of critical
manufacturing processes and of products; and, the federal authority
(FDA), which maintains responsibility for public safety by ensuring
the competence of the DCB's, keeping the system honest by enforcing
compliance with law, and by maintaining a universal system of
postmarketing surveillance. The system is characterized by the
reliance on objectively defined law, clear standards and well-defined
responsibility. It relies, as far as possible, on private, non-governmental,
organizations. The plan follows in most details the workings of
the European Union medical device regulatory system.<BR>

<P>
<b>Basic Principles</b>
<P>
All medical devices are classified, using clear
objective criteria, into one of four classes (I, IIa, IIb, and
III). Devices presenting the highest level of risk and complexity
are placed in the higher numbered classes. Devices may be marketed
only if they conform with a comprehensive series of &quot;essential
requirements.&quot; As far as possible, such conformance will
be ensured in practice by adhering to relevant internationally
agreed upon objective standards. For all classes of devices, except
Class I, a DCB must audit the manufacturer periodically to confirm
such conformance. The number of areas audited and the stringency
of the audit depends on the class. However, in all cases, the
manufacturer has a choice of methods to demonstrate conformance.
In general, the manufacturer can either demonstrate conformance
of his quality assurance systems or conformance of the product
itself. Combinations of these two routes are permitted. In all
cases the manufacturer must have a system for monitoring and acting
upon reports of a device malfunction after sale. In addition,
the FDA acts as a central repository of such information when
it involves a serious threat to patient safety as it is in a position
to monitor the investigation of such events, especially when it
involves similar situations arising with several manufacturers.
The FDA may, for cause, require that a device be withdrawn from
the market if the manufacturer has not ensured that it meets the
essential requirements or if the DCB has not acted competently.
In addition, criminal charges may be brought in the case of fraud
or criminal negligence.<BR>

<P>
<b>Self-certification by Manufacturers</b>
<P>
Device innovation is often characterized by
many small incremental changes. A method of rapid certification
of new products facilitates this. For Class I devices, the manufacture
may self-certify conformance with the essential requirements.
Manufacturers who maintain a total quality assurance system may
self-certify new Class IIa and IIb products between the periodic
audits of their DCB. Class III products always require premarketing
design approval by a DCB. In addition, for Class III devices,
the FDA must be notified 90 days prior to marketing to allow time
for the FDA to elect to review the appropriateness of the certification
process.<BR>

<P>
<b>Good Manufacturing Practice Inspection</b>
<P>
The FDA's current auditing of manufacturers
for Good Manufacturing Practices would be replaced by the DCB's
certification of the manufacturer's quality assurance systems.
Such certification would often exceed FDA standards as it could
include certification of design quality assurance. It would also
be done far more frequently than current FDA inspections. <BR>

<P>
<b>Labeling and Off-Label Use</b>
<P>
Currently, a new application to the FDA is
needed whenever the manufacturer claims a new use for a device,
or even if the manufacture wishes to distribute reprints from
the scientific literature concerning a new use. This is often
so expensive and time consuming that the manufacture &quot;ignores&quot;
such clinical practice, resulting in widespread &quot;off-label&quot;
uses. In most cases, in the new system, the manufacture will be
able to self-certify such label changes (subject to the unusual
monitoring by the DCB).<BR>

<P>
<b>Timeliness of Approvals</b>
<P>
The current system has been characterized by
such slow approvals that venture capital has become scarce and
manufacturers have been forced to relocate critical operations
offshore. Approvals under the new system should be expeditious
as competitive forces will only tolerate DCB's capable of responding
to the market.<BR>

<P>
<b>International Harmonization</b>
<P>
Since the new system will be based on standards
and procedures virtually identical to those of the European Union,
it should be possible for a manufacturer to obtain both U.S. and
European approval using the same documentation and inspections.
In can be predicted that organizations will be certified both
as U.S. DCB's and European &quot;notified bodies.&quot; <BR>

<P>
<b>Transition</b>
<P>
A two to three year transition period is envisioned
so that devices under current review can be approved under the
existing system, if the manufacture should so elect. After a suitable
period, only products certified under the new system would be
allowed access to the market.

<P><br></blockquote><center><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small><P><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
