<h2>Footnotes</h2>

<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Overview</FONT></B>
<OL>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">See <I>White Paper on Four Areas of Relevance
to New Drug Development and Review in the United States</I>, Tufts
Center for the Study of Drug Development, September 9, 1994, pp.
23-35; and Written Testimony of Kenneth I. Kaitin, Ph.D., Associate
Director, Tufts Center for the Study of Drug Development, House
Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations, May 25, 1995.</FONT>

<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial"></FONT>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">See Tufts <I>White Paper, </I>pp. 4-22.</FONT>
</OL>

<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial"></FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">3. See following paper by Ralph A. Epstein.
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">Notes - Section 1</FONT></B>
<P>
<ol>
<li> Clearly, the FDA reports to more than one
Congressional committee, so that the Weingast and Moran argument
is more complicated than the idea of a single, dominant overseer.
 Also, it is not clear that the FDA has responded much to advice
to loosen up, which suggests that it is more of a captive of committees
which criticize the agency for being too easy on industry.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<li>  The following discussion is meant to be
suggestive of how to analyze this case in slightly more formal
terms.  It can be skipped without loss of continuity.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<li>   An important semantical point needs to
be made here. Self-certification in the present discussion simply
means letting the market work, including the adoption of the standards
under which self-certification would take place. In other contexts
in this study self-certification will mean letting firms meet
an exogeneously determined set of standards (e.g., for Class I
medical devices) on their own. Government is not involved in the
former case, while it is involved in setting and policing standards
in the latter case.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<li>  The &quot;lemons&quot; problem resides in
the fact that buyers do not know the true quality of products
before they purchase and use them.  Hence, they tend to overvalue
lower quality products and to undervalue higher quality products.
 This means that only the lower quality products will be sold
in market equilibrium.  Owners of higher quality products will
not supply them for sales because they are systematically undervalued
by the market.  The market for used cars may be used as an example
of the &quot;lemons&quot; problem.  The analysis can also be translated
to the market for medical treatment. There is a pervasive history
of fraud in medical treatment and a tendency for the system to
degenerate into scams. The ease of fraud and scams is the reason
alternative medicines are so popular, such as shark cartilage
for cancer and arthritis treatment.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<li>  The discussion here refers to patent monopolies
for particular individual products and not to overall company
profits.</FONT>
<P>
<li>  Department of Transportation, Federal Aviation
Regulations, Number 14, Part 21. These regulations provide details
on required testing for all parts, components, and subsystems,
as well as required flight standards. They also provide detailed
guidelines for organizing a test program and the required certification
procedures.</FONT>
<P>
<li>  There are a few exceptions to this rule.
Experimental aircraft may not have a type certification. Experimental
aircraft include most home-built aircraft, many military aircraft,
and heavily modified conventional aircraft.</FONT>
<P>
<li>  For an interesting discussion of the FAA
as a model for drug regulation, see Urquhart (1995).</FONT>
<P>
<li>  It should be stressed that harmonization
talks are presently ongoing among the U.S. and other countries
about reciprocity in drug approvals. A key aspect of these discussions
whether the U.S. system would move closer to those in Europe,
or vice-versa.</FONT>
</ol>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">END SECTION - 1<BR>
</FONT></B>
