the Performance and Contribution of the U.S. Medical Device Industry&quot;,
a report prepared for the Health Industry Manufacturers Association,
p. 20.</FONT>
<P>
<li>  Wilkerson Group (1995), p. 13.</FONT>
<P>
<li>  Briones (1995), p. 9 (citing Price Waterhouse
calculations).</FONT>
<P>
<li>  Briones (1995), pp. 15-22. (Citing FD Office
of Device Evaluation [ODE]) annual reports of 1993 and 1994).
The vast majority of these applications are 510(k) &quot;notifications&quot;.
In 1994 there were a total of 5,498 510(k) decisions approving
the claim of substantial equivalence and 135 decisions disapproving
the claim, while there were only 43 Premarket Approval (PMA) applications.
The number of 510(k) applications was little changed during the
period 1988 through 1994 while the number of PMA applications
decreased by a factor of two.</FONT>
<P>
<li>  In 1992, Commissioner Kessler convened a
committee, chaired by the director of the Office of Drug Evaluation
(Robert Temple), to evaluate the medical device approval systems.
The Temple Report advocated basing device approvals on clinical
trials similar to those used for drug approvals.</FONT>
<P>
<li>  Dickinson JG. Fixing the Liability Laws.
Medical Device &amp; Diagnostic Industry. 16(8):26-28, 1994. Dickinson
cites testimony before the Senate Governmental Affairs/Regulation
and Governmental Information Subcommittee explaining why Du Pont
no longer supplies biomedical materials. For one implant alone,
Du Pont has expended $8 million dollars per year for 5 years to
defend itself against 259 liability cases (of which it won 258).
&quot;Each implant contained about five cents's worth of Teflon.&quot;</FONT>
<P>
<li>  The 1938 Federal Food, Drug, and Cosmetic
Act gave the FDA statutory authority to take regulatory action
if a device was produced under unsanitary conditions, was dangerous
if used as directed, or it's labeling was misleading, did not
contain adequate instructions for use or did not identify the
manufacturer. For a legislative history of device regulation through
the late 1980's see: Hutt PB, A History of Government Regulation
of Adulteration and Misbranding of Medical Devices, chapter 2,
pp. 17-33 in Estrin NF, ed., The Medical Device Industry, Marcel
Decker, New York, 1990.</FONT>
<P>
<li>  Kessler DA, Pape SM, Sundwall DN. The Federal
Regulation of Medical Devices. New England Journal of Medicine
317:357-66, 1987. In this article, Dr. Kessler (before he became
FDA Commissioner) wrote: &quot;the FDA's extensive reliance on
the 510(k) pathway to reduce the number of devices that require
premarketing approval - and consequently its own workload - is
destined to fail. As technology advances, the number of devices
legitimately found to be substantially equivalent to devices marketed
before 1976 will diminish markedly. If the FDA does not soon develop
other acceptable mechanisms for dealing with new devices, practical
considerations will force it to stretch the statute further, making
the regulation of medical devices even more perplexing.&quot;</FONT>
<P>
<li>  Less than the Sum of its Parts. A Report
of the Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations of the Committee
on Energy and Commerce, U.S. House of Representatives, pp. 9-11,
1993. </FONT>
<P>
<li>  FDA Office of Device Evaluation, personal
communication (December 13, 1995). The use of median times obscures
the fact that the distribution is skewed towards longer times.
Thus the mean elapsed time in 1994 was 216 days.</FONT>
<P>
<li>  Wilkerson Group (1995), p. 78.</FONT>
<P>
<li>  The 1976 Food Drug and Cosmetic Act at least
technically offered the opportunity for the manufacturer to market
a device under section 510(k) 90 days after notification of the
FDA. The 1990 amendments removed this option and the manufacturer,
under the threat of severe penalties, must await an FDA &quot;order&quot;
giving permission to go to market.</FONT>
<P>
<li>  Briones (1995), p. 17. Statistical analysis
of data based on the date the PMA was submitted, by necessity,
does not include PMA's that were still pending at the time of
analysis. When these PMA's are finally acted upon, perhaps many
years after originally submitted, the average elapsed time will
increase. This phenomenon is more important for PMA's than 510(k)'s
as they typically require much more time and are not acted upon
in the year that they are filed.</FONT>
<P>
<li>  Wilkerson Group (1995), pp. 78-89. This
contains an economic model of the costs of regulatory delay using
estimates of the time required for device approvals in the United
States and the European Union. The model is based on survey data.
Of the companies surveyed, 61 percent market products offshore
before marketing in the United States. Sixty nine percent anticipated
that the delay would be between 1 and 3 years (pp. 89-91).</FONT>
<P>
<li>  George WW. Which Way FDA?. Medical Device
&amp; Diagnostic Industry. 17(12):22-24, 1995. William George,
CEO of Medtronics, states that of their &quot;last 15 major new
product lines or ventures, all have been developed, tested and
produced first in Europe. All will be available first to patients
overseas well before they are introduced to patients in the United
States. Overall, the gap between commercial availability of new
therapies in Europe and the United States has widened from 1 to
2 years to 5 to 7 years.&quot; The author has heard similar statements
from knowledgeable sources in the American device industry.</FONT>
<P>
<li>  In 1994, the Gallop Organization interviewed
58 executives of member companies of the American Electronics
Association and prepared a &quot;Survey of Medical Device Manufacturers
Concerning the Strategic and Economic Impact of the Federal Regulatory
Process.&quot; They looked at the impact of the experience of
these companies with the current 510(k) approval process. Fifteen
percent of these executives reported that their experience has
led them to relocate manufacturing operations outside of the United
States, 35% reported placing a greater emphasis on R&amp;D outside
the U.S. and 59% reported that more products are released outside
the U.S. that in the past.</FONT>
<P>
<li>  Commissioner Kessler in his April 6, 1995
statement before the Senate Committee on Labor and Human Resources
stated that &quot;Today, the Clinton Administration is announcing
a number of initiatives to improve the speed and efficiency of
the drug and device review process... I would like to submit for
the record FDA's report on regulatory reform in drug and medical
device review. These reforms ... have been developed under the
leadership of Vice President Gore's National Performance Review...
Some of the reforms we announce speak directly to reduced time
for review and approval. Others aim to reduce excessive regulatory
burdens... They will result ... in annual cost savings for industry
of $500 million.&quot; There is currently little debate concerning
whether reform is needed. The only question is which reforms are
best.</FONT>
<P>
<li>  The FDA has recently announced it's &quot;policy
on the development of standards with respect to international
harmonization of regulatory requirements and guidelines&quot;
(Federal Register, vol. 60, no. 196, pp.53078-84, October 11,
1995). The FDA states that &quot;harmonization enhances public
health protection and improves governmental efficiencies by reducing
both unwarranted contradictory regulatory requirements and redundant
applications of similar requirements by multiple regulatory bodies.&quot;
However, taken as a whole, the announced policy has so many caveats
that it is evident that the FDA is still not enthusiastically
embracing the harmonization of standards with Western Europe.
In fact the announcement overtly states that this &quot;policy
document does not ... bind FDA in any way.&quot;</FONT>
<P>
<li>  European Council Directive of 14 June 1993
Concerning Medical Devices, Annex I, gives the details of the
14 essential requirements.</FONT>
<P>
<li>  The question of why the FDA, despite the
mandates of the 1976 law, failed to develop performance standards,
while the European system successfully relies upon them is elucidated
by Commissioner Kessler writing (NEJM 317:357-66, 1987) that &quot;the
development of 800 performance standards for the 800 types of
Class II devices, which has been estimated to require 50,000 staff
years, would probably exceed the capacity of the agency under
any circumstances.&quot;  In the European system there is no need
for a vast staff as they take full advantage of the myriad of
non-governmental standards setting bodies in a multitude of countries;
they have the flexibility to use generic standards as well as
standards that apply only to a single device; they, in many cases,
use standards to validate the manufacturer's quality assurance
systems instead of individual device standards; and finally they
allow the manufacture to devise <I>ad hoc</I> methods of proving
conformance with the &quot;essential requirements&quot; instead
of or to supplement relying on published standards. This approach
has allowed for more flexibility than relying primarily on a monolithic
federal agency.</FONT>
<P>
<li>  Annex IX of the Medical Device Directive
contains the details of the classification criteria.</FONT>
<P>
<li>  The full set of EU quality assurance standards
(which are similar to the ISO 9000 series of standards commonly
used in the United States) is equivalent to a super set of the
FDA's GMP requirements in that they also include standards for
ensuring the quality of the design process. The FDA has announced
that it intends to add design quality assurance to its GMP's in
the future.</FONT>
<P>
<li>  Magazine AH, Hunt MI. The U.S. Medical Device
Industry Moves Offshore. Medical Device &amp; Diagnostic Industry.
17(8):72-79, 1995. According to a recent survey, &quot;seventy
percent of all companies and 84% of development-stage firm moving
clinical trials offshore rate 'FDA uncertainty and unpredictability'
as a critical element in their decision.&quot;</FONT>
<P>
<li>  Wilkerson (1955) pp. 217-27. This lists
100 specific medical devices, currently available in Europe, Canada,
Australia and/or Japan, which are currently not available to patients
in the United States.  Eventual FDA approval is expected for most
of these products. In general, these devices relate to the diagnosis
and treatment of severe disease. For example, 31 of the 100 are
related to coronary artery disease, structural cardiac abnormalities
or congestive heart failure. To the extent that they are more
efficacious than devices currently available in the United States,
regulatory delay may be responsible for unnecessary morbidity
and mortality.</FONT>
<P>
<li>  Less than the Sum of its Parts (1993) p.
81. The House report states: &quot;Clinical utility is the Agency's
[FDA's] requirement that a device manufacturer prove not only
does the device work as claimed, but that patient's health also
improves as a result of the device's action.&quot; &quot;Since
... ODE is barely able to perform the review presently required
by statute, it makes little sense for it to add routinely the
burden of assessing clinical utility to its review process.&quot;
 There is a critical distinction between the EU's concept of requiring
evidence of clinical efficacy and the FDA's requirement for evidence
of clinical utility. The former is related to demonstrating that
the device has the claimed effect; the latter, that the device's
effect is clinically beneficial. For example, the manufacture
of a mechanical ventilator that breathes for a patient may claim
that it delivers large breath volumes at a slow rate. The EU system
would require that this claim be verified and that the gas really
goes into the patient's lungs as claimed; the FDA system would
require that it be shown that this type of ventilation is, in
some sense, good for some subset of patients. In the EU system,
such medical questions are normally outside the domain of the
device regulations (unless, of course, the device manufacturer
makes an implicit or explicit claim of clinical utility).</FONT>
<P>
<li>  Less than the Sum of its Parts (1993) pp.
71-3. This congressional report quotes the head of the FDA Division
of Product Surveillance as stating that the current device reporting
&quot;system doesn't work and everyone knows it doesn't.&quot;
The report concludes that &quot;The weakness of CDRH's MDR system
reflects an FDA-wide problem with its failure to use management
information systems effectively&quot; and that little has changed
since the GAO came to a similar conclusion in their 1989 report.
The report continues on p. 91: &quot;The MDR system currently
cannot serve as an early warning system ... and it makes little
sense to invest additional resources into this system given its
many flaws. The Agency's chronic problems in this area may make
it necessary to have an independent expert contractor develop
a practical and useful system.&quot; For devices, because they
way that they are actually used cannot be fully determined before
actual marketing, postmarket surveillance is at least as important
as premarket review. Fortunately, it is in the interest of responsible
manufacturers to have their own, generally very effective, systems
to act on device problems discovered in the post-marketing period.</FONT>
</ol><P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">END SECTION - 3 <BR>
<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
