<title>BAN PARTIAL-BIRTH ABORTIONS</title>
<body>
<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/perspective/perspective.gif">
<h2>BAN PARTIAL-BIRTH ABORTIONS</h2>
<hr size=3 width=50%><p>
<i>by</i>
<p>
<i>Gracie S. Hsu</i></center>
<p>
It isn't often that congressmen and senators have the opportunity
to vote on something as important as preserving human life.  But
those in the House of Representatives will have such an opportunity
during the first week in November, and those in the Senate may
have the opportunity shortly thereafter.
<p>
Rep. Charles Canady (R-Fla.) has introduced H.R. 1833, which would
ban partial-birth abortions.  The companion bill, S. 939, has
been introduced by Sen. Bob Smith (R-N.H.).  This important bill
should gain support from people across the political spectrum
because the bill helps to protect innocent human life from being
exterminated outside the womb.  Moreover, because the bill focuses
on the partial-birth abortion procedure, it educates both the
Congress and the public about the reality of the abortion act.
<p>
Rep. Canady's bill already has more than 150 cosponsors on both
sides of the aisle.  (The Senate bill has six.)  The House Judiciary
Committee passed H.R. 1833 overwhelmingly in July, and even the
12-member American Medical Association's legislative council voted
<I>unanimously</I> to <I>endorse</I> the Partial-Birth Abortion
Ban Act.  When asked about the council's decision, one legislative
council representative called the procedure &quot;basically repulsive,&quot;
saying that it wasn't a &quot;recognized medical technique.&quot;
<p>
...And it isn't, or at least it shouldn't be.
<p>
First of all, partial-birth abortions involve aborting partially-delivered
babies from four and a half months into the pregnancy up to even
the <I>ninth month</I>.  The procedure consists of  partially
delivering the live baby feet first so that all but the head is
outside the mother's womb.  The head remains in the uterus while
the abortionist kills the baby by stabbing surgical scissors into
the base of its head, then suctioning out the brain by a small
tube, and then completing the delivery of the now-dead baby. 
The legislation makes it a crime to perform this procedure except
to save the mother's life.  A woman undergoing the abortion would
not be penalized and could not sue the abortionist, but the abortionist
could be punished  for up to two years in prison and/or fined.
<p>
Ohio Registered Nurse Brenda Pratt Shafer, who has assisted in
three partial-birth abortions, describes the process this way:
<p>
&quot;Dr. Haskell brought the ultrasound in and hooked it up so
that he could see the baby. On the ultrasound screen, I could see the heart 
beating. I asked Dr. Haskell, and he told me that, 'Yes, that is the heartbeat.'
 As Dr. Haskell watched the baby on the ultrasound screen, he
went in with forceps and grabbed the baby's legs and brought them
down into the birth canal.  Then he delivered the body and the
arms, all the way up to the neck.  At this point, only the baby's
head was still inside.  The baby's body was moving.  His little
fingers were clasping together.  He was kicking his feet.  All
the while his little head was still stuck inside.  Dr. Haskell
took a pair of scissors and inserted them into the back of the
baby's head.  Then he opened the scissors up.  Then he stuck the
high-powered suction tube into the hole and sucked the baby's
brains out.  I almost threw up as I watched him do these things....&quot;
<p>
&quot;I never realized how perfect these babies really are at
this point.  When you hear the word 'fetus,' I think a lot of
people think, as I did, of just a blob of cells, or a mass or
something.  It was very revealing to me.  I don't think about
abortion the same way anymore.&quot;
<p>
According to the Alan Guttmacher Institute, the research arm of
Planned Parenthood, approximately 13,000 abortions every year
occur after the 20th week of pregnancy (four and a half months).
 While it is not known how many of these are partial-birth abortions,
two abortionists, including Dr. Haskell, have said publicly in
different interviews that they have performed 3,000 &quot;late
term&quot; abortions, including the partial-birth procedure, between
the two of them.  Rep. Canady's bill is a first step to preventing
the horror of late-term abortions.
<p>
Public opinion polls show that an overwhelming majority reject
late-term abortions.  Yet, the Supreme Court has never dealt with
the issue of a &quot;partially-born&quot; child.  The Partial-Birth
Abortion Ban Act will rightly outlaw the most barbaric of the
late-term abortion procedures.
<p>
Proponents of abortion will argue that all abortions are needed
in cases of &quot;health of the mother.&quot;  This reasoning
is flawed because typically, courts have defined &quot;health
of the mother&quot; clauses very broadly to encompass &quot;all
factors -- physical, emotional, psychological, familial, and the
woman's age -- relevant to the well-being of the patient.&quot;
(<I>Doe v. Bolton</I>, 410 U.S.C. at 192 (1973), emphasis added.)
In fact, of the many reasons why a mother would elect to abort
her unborn child (i.e., parental disapproval, physical inconvenience,
emotional distress), none would fall outside the realm of this
&quot;exception.&quot;
<p>
Similarly, the case is often made for abortions that are &quot;medically
necessary.&quot;  However, this is equivalent to abortion on demand.
William Hamilton, vice president of the Planned Parenthood Federation
of America, told Knight-Ridder Newspapers that &quot;medically
necessary&quot; means &quot;anything a doctor and a woman construe
to be in her best interest, whether prenatal care or abortion.&quot;
Judith Feder, a Clinton Administration health official, stated
that &quot;the decision of the woman and the physician&quot; determines
whether a service can be considered &quot;medically necessary.&quot;
<p>
This modest legislation provides a means for a civil society to
register its objections by banning this unwarranted act of violence
against a helpless member of our human family.
<p>
-- 10/31/95
<p>
<center>***</center>
<p>
<i>Gracie S. Hsu, M.H.S., is a policy analyst at the Family Research
Council, a Washington, D.C.-based research and advocacy organization.</i>

