<h2>The Telecommunications Revolution</h2>
<h3>An American Opportunity</h3>
<hr width="50%">
<h2>ACKNOWLEDGEMENTS</h2>
</center><blockquote>
<P>
 In any undertaking of this magnitude, the final product is made
possible by the generous efforts of many people.  The Progress
&amp; Freedom Foundation extends its thanks to those currently
serving with the government, including the Federal Communications
Commission, who gave insight, comments, and/or suggestions.  In
addition, thanks are due to many elsewhere in government service
who commented on specific proposals.  
<P>
 The Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation expresses its appreciation
to the following members of the Working Group which assisted with
this Report:  Dr. Robert Crandall, The Brookings Institution,
James Gattuso, Esq.,  Citizens for a Sound Economy, Dr. Thomas
Hazlett,   U.C. Davis,  Peter W. Huber, Esq., The  Manhattan Institute,
 Peter Pitsch, Esq., The Hudson Institute, Kenneth Robinson, Esq.,
J. Gregory Sidak, Esq., The  American Enterprise Institute, and
Adam Thierer, The Heritage Foundation.  Members of  the Working
Group participated with the project solely in their individual
capacity and do not represent the views and/or position of their
respective institutions and/or telecommunications affiliations.
  Any remaining errors or omissions are attributable to the Progress
&amp; Freedom Foundation.
<P>
 The Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation extends special thanks
to Julianne Lee, with the Foundation's telecommunications group,
for her able assistance in completing the project.  Rachel Krajc,
Special Assistant to the Foundation's Senior Fellows, also performed
above the call of duty by her tireless efforts, including coaxing
 miracles from a recalcitrant laser jet printer and coordinating
the Working Group.  Rick O'Donnell, Communications Director, also
gave generously of his time and skills. Tara Lowry provided invaluable
assistance in coordination and communications. William Myers,
Bethany Noble and Garland McCoy also provided warm support and
encouragement.
<P>
 David Colton would like to dedicate his portion of this effort
to his father.
<P>
Footnotes and references appearing in the full document were excluded from this on-line version of the report to facilitate reading and speed the document to the Internet community.
